Machine coding


Create a library for fair resource utilization for shared multi-tenant pub/sub system
Use in-process queues to emulate persistent queues
Publishers publish messages in bulk (e.g. 1000 messages at once) usually
When multiple publishers do publish in bulk, the worker process spends most of their time
for 1 tenant only at a time if they consume from a single queue for all tenants.
This causes delay in processing messages for other tenants. We want to solve this.
We want to fairly distribute message processing for multiple tenants within a single process.
For publishers keep the interface simple that they all publish to a single queue. A message in the queue can belong to any tenant. We can keep a key like “tenant_id” within the message for this.
Use a pool of workers (VirtualThreads/Goroutines(only for golang) with a max limit per process e.g. 100) to consumer messages for all tenants.
Create a library which accepts the queue and pool of workers as input and it internally does the fair distribution for all tenants.
Expectation
Code should work for mocked publishers and consumers. In consumer, we can just print the message to stdout with some time delay to test.

Output:

Processing: Message-0 from tenant-B | Tenant: tenant-B
Processing: Message-0 from tenant-A | Tenant: tenant-A
Processing: Message-1 from tenant-A | Tenant: tenant-A
Processing: Message-1 from tenant-B | Tenant: tenant-B
Processing: Message-2 from tenant-A | Tenant: tenant-A
Processing: Message-2 from tenant-B | Tenant: tenant-B
Processing: Message-3 from tenant-B | Tenant: tenant-B
Processing: Message-3 from tenant-A | Tenant: tenant-A





